BY Mrs Hemans
Child, amidst the flowers at play,
While the red light fades away;
Mother, with thine earnest eye,
Ever following silently
Father, by the breeze Of eve
Call'd thy harvest-work to leaves
Pray Ere yet the dark hours be,
Lift the heart and bend the knee.
Traveller, in the strangers land,
Far from thine own household band;
Mourner, haunted by the tone
OF a voice from this world gone;
Captive, in whose narrow cell
Sunshine hath not leave 10 dwell:
Sailor, on the darkening sea,
Lift the heart and bend the knee.
Warrior, that from battle won,
Breathest now at set OF sun;
Woman, o'er the lowly slain,
Weeping on his burial. plain;
Ye that triumph, ye hat sigh,
Kindred by one holy tie!
Heavens first star alike ye see
Lift the heart and bend the knee!
TILE HOUR OF PRAYER.

James Armor

EpITApH. inscribed upon the tombstone Of Xantip-
pc Thomas, wife OF Andrew Thomas who scold
ed herself to death in the early part OF the last
century:


Here lies the wife of Neighbor Thomas,
Whom death in mercy carried from US;
For, when alive, she was so old,
So ugly, slut,ish, such scold.
That round about her for mile,
All things were in constant broil
I've known her storm at such a rate
Ths, even the chimney back would sweat;
Trammels through fear Jorge. TO hold.
And red hot coals Of fire grow cold.
Her husband never dropp'd tear
Till he had placed her body here;
And then he bubbered like lout,
For fear she'd scratch her passage out.

full articles.headline: TILE HOUR OF PRAYER.
full articles.article:
BY Mrs Hemans
Child, amidst the flowers at play,
While the red light fades away;
Mother, with thine earnest eye,
Ever following silently
Father, by the breeze Of eve
Call'd thy harvest-work to leaves
Pray Ere yet the dark hours be,
Lift the heart and bend the knee.
Traveller, in the strangers land,
Far from thine own household band;
Mourner, haunted by the tone
OF a voice from this world gone;
Captive, in whose narrow cell
Sunshine hath not leave 10 dwell:
Sailor, on the darkening sea,
Lift the heart and bend the knee.
Warrior, that from battle won,
Breathest now at set OF sun;
Woman, o'er the lowly slain,
Weeping on his burial. plain;
Ye that triumph, ye hat sigh,
Kindred by one holy tie!
Heavens first star alike ye see
Lift the heart and bend the knee!

James Armor

EpITApH. inscribed upon the tombstone Of Xantip-
pc Thomas, wife OF Andrew Thomas who scold
ed herself to death in the early part OF the last
century:


Here lies the wife of Neighbor Thomas,
Whom death in mercy carried from US;
For, when alive, she was so old,
So ugly, slut,ish, such scold.
That round about her for mile,
All things were in constant broil
I've known her storm at such a rate
Ths, even the chimney back would sweat;
Trammels through fear Jorge. TO hold.
And red hot coals Of fire grow cold.
Her husband never dropp'd tear
Till he had placed her body here;
And then he bubbered like lout,
For fear she'd scratch her passage out.
